Automation is section 6.0 of the CCNA exam
topics, and it is 10% of the exam.

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:44.120
Read these exam topics carefully.

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:49.620
They state that you have to be able to explain,
compare, describe, recognize, and interpret

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:51.280
different things.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:56.340
However you don’t actually have to be able
to automate networking tasks yourself.

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:00.680
Cisco just wants you to understand various
topics related to network automation, but

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:05.940
the actual hands-on automation is left for
other certifications at the CCNP level and

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:10.330
above, as well as the DevNet certification
track.

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:16.670
In this video we’ll mostly be looking at
these three topics, 6.1, 6.2, and 6.3, giving

00:01:16.670 --> 00:01:20.880
a general overview of network automation and
its benefits.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:24.070
Here’s what we’ll cover.

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:28.140
First I’ll give a quick overview of why
network automation is used, and some of its

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:29.140
benefits.

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:34.500
I’ll then explain the logical planes of
network functions, the data plane, control

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:36.840
plane, and management plane.

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:38.770
Maybe you’ve heard of these before, but
maybe you haven’t.

00:01:38.770 --> 00:01:43.790
I’ll explain what they are, because they
are essential to understanding the next topic,

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:46.020
software-defined networking.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:52.210
While introducing SDN, I’ll also introduce
APIs and data serialization.

00:01:52.210 --> 00:01:56.231
As I said, this video will be an introduction
to all of these topics, and then I’ll cover

00:01:56.231 --> 00:01:59.920
them in greater detail in the next few videos.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:04.119
And make sure to watch until the end of the
video for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:02:04.119 --> 00:02:08.849
Software’s ExSim for CCNA, the best practice
exams for the CCNA.

00:02:08.849 --> 00:02:13.079
So let’s look at network automation.

00:02:13.079 --> 00:02:18.299
Previous versions of the CCNA focused on the
traditional model of managing and controlling

00:02:18.299 --> 00:02:19.299
networks.

00:02:19.299 --> 00:02:23.660
Actually, the current version does too, but
you are expected to have a basic understanding

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:28.230
of various topics related to network automation,
and that’s what we’ll focus on in these

00:02:28.230 --> 00:02:30.580
next few videos.

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:35.349
In the traditional model, engineers manage
devices one at a time by connecting to their

00:02:35.349 --> 00:02:37.739
CLI via SSH.

00:02:37.739 --> 00:02:43.130
Telnet connections are possible too of course,
as well as connections to the console port.

00:02:43.130 --> 00:02:45.799
Some devices support a GUI also.

00:02:45.799 --> 00:02:49.420
But the main point here is that devices are
managed and configured one by one.

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:54.890
So, let’s say your company wants to add
a loopback interface to all of their routers.

00:02:54.890 --> 00:03:00.940
You connect to R1 using SSH, configure the
loopback interface, save the config, and exit

00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:01.940
out.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:03.969
Then you do it for R2.

00:03:03.969 --> 00:03:05.310
And R3.

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:06.609
And R4.

00:03:06.609 --> 00:03:10.650
And every one of the hundreds of routers in
your company network.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:13.950
So what are some downsides to managing a network
like this?

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:15.400
Here are a few.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.790
First, typos and other small mistakes are
common.

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:23.609
I’m sure that as you’ve been doing practice
labs for the CCNA you’ve made typos at some

00:03:23.609 --> 00:03:24.959
point.

00:03:24.959 --> 00:03:28.799
Sometimes you realize it immediately and fix
it, but then other times it can take a lot

00:03:28.799 --> 00:03:34.700
of time troubleshooting to find that the problem
was just a typo in an IP address, for example.

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:39.769
It is also time consuming and can be very
inefficient especially in large-scale networks.

00:03:39.769 --> 00:03:43.890
Repetitive tasks can be automated and performed
in a fraction of the time.

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:48.689
And here’s another issue that might be harder
to imagine if you don’t have any work experience

00:03:48.689 --> 00:03:51.180
as a network engineer yet.

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:57.029
It is difficult to ensure that all devices
adhere to the organization’s standard configurations.

00:03:57.029 --> 00:04:01.090
An organization will usually have standard
configuration templates that they use for

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:05.459
their devices, and it’s important to ensure
that these policies are upheld throughout

00:04:05.459 --> 00:04:06.620
the network.

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:12.579
However, as individual network engineers make
individual changes over the years, the configurations

00:04:12.579 --> 00:04:15.650
can start to drift away from the standard.

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:20.030
This can cause issues down the line, for example
making troubleshooting more difficult because

00:04:20.030 --> 00:04:24.940
the devices don’t all have similar configurations.

00:04:24.940 --> 00:04:29.139
Of course, when I talk about the disadvantages
of the traditional model, I’m talking about

00:04:29.139 --> 00:04:34.289
it in comparison to network management and
operation using automation.

00:04:34.289 --> 00:04:36.569
Network automation offers many key benefits.

00:04:36.569 --> 00:04:38.099
Here are some of them.

00:04:38.099 --> 00:04:42.680
First, human error is reduced, for example
typos.

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:48.039
Instead of a network engineer directly logging
in to the CLI and manually entering commands,

00:04:48.039 --> 00:04:50.690
the task can be automated.

00:04:50.690 --> 00:04:52.599
Networks become much more scalable.

00:04:52.599 --> 00:04:57.470
New network deployments, network-wide changes,
as well as troubleshooting can be implemented

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.650
in a fraction of the time.

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:04.720
Also, network-wide policy compliance can be
assured, for example making sure all devices

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:10.400
have the proper standard configurations, all
devices have the correct software versions,

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:11.449
etc.

00:05:11.449 --> 00:05:17.210
And the improved efficiency of network operations
reduces the opex, meaning operating expenses,

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:18.740
of the network.

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:25.550
Each task requires fewer man-hours, and engineers
can focus on more important things.

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:29.830
For example, in the same situation as before
when we need to add a new loopback interface

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:35.099
to hundreds of routers, instead of logging
into each router one by one and manually configuring

00:05:35.099 --> 00:05:39.810
a loopback interface, which could take hours
of time, a python script could perform the

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:44.650
task and make the proper configurations in
a fraction of the time.

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:48.470
Note that there are various tools and methods
that can be used to automate tasks in the

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:49.620
network.

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:51.120
Here are some examples.

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:56.500
SDN, Ansible, Puppet, Python scripts, and
many more.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:06:00.430
Throughout these videos I’ll introduce multiple
different methods, but for the rest of this

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:07.199
video let’s focus on the concept of SDN,
software-defined networking.

00:06:07.199 --> 00:06:12.219
To understand SDN, you have to understand
the logical planes of network functions.

00:06:12.219 --> 00:06:13.909
Let me explain.

00:06:13.909 --> 00:06:15.979
Here you can see two simple questions.

00:06:15.979 --> 00:06:17.580
What does a router do?

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:19.560
And what does a switch do?

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:21.880
Here are some example answers.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:27.569
A router forwards messages between networks
by examining information in the Layer 3 header.

00:06:27.569 --> 00:06:33.260
And a switch forwards messages within a LAN
by examining information in the Layer 2 header.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:36.750
Okay, but is that all that routers and switches
do?

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:41.789
A router also uses a routing protocol like
OSPF to share routing information with others

00:06:41.789 --> 00:06:44.389
routers and build a routing table.

00:06:44.389 --> 00:06:49.879
It also uses ARP to build an ARP table, mapping
IP addresses to MAC addresses.

00:06:49.879 --> 00:06:54.310
For example, it would use ARP to learn the
MAC address of the next hop router when forwarding

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:55.939
a packet.

00:06:55.939 --> 00:06:59.229
It also uses Syslog to keep logs of events
that occur.

00:06:59.229 --> 00:07:04.650
We are also able to use SSH to connect to
a router and manage it.

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:09.150
And of course there are many more things that
routers do, as we’ve learned in this course.

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:10.770
How about switches?

00:07:10.770 --> 00:07:15.790
A switch uses STP to ensure that there are
no Layer 2 loops in the network.

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:20.789
It builds a MAC address table by examining
the source MAC address of frames.

00:07:20.789 --> 00:07:24.810
Like a router, it also uses protocols like
Syslog and SSH.

00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:29.939
Those are just some examples, there are many
more functions of a switch.

00:07:29.939 --> 00:07:34.169
And if it’s a Layer 3 switch, it can have
the same functions of a router, like using

00:07:34.169 --> 00:07:36.590
OSPF to build a routing table.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:40.590
Anyway, the point is that routers and switches
do a lot of different things.

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:44.770
They don’t just forward messages at Layer
2 or Layer 3.

00:07:44.770 --> 00:07:51.800
And these various functions of network devices
can be logically divided up, logically categorized,

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:54.569
into what we call planes.

00:07:54.569 --> 00:07:57.029
Typically we divide the functions into three
planes.

00:07:57.029 --> 00:08:00.580
The data plane, the control plane, and the
management plane.

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:05.050
Let’s take a look at the functions of each
plane.

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:07.349
First let’s look at the data plane.

00:08:07.349 --> 00:08:12.030
All tasks involved in forwarding user data
from one interface to another are part of

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:13.199
the data plane.

00:08:13.199 --> 00:08:18.630
So, this is what you usually think of a router
or switch doing, forwarding messages.

00:08:18.630 --> 00:08:22.919
A router receives a message, looks for the
most specific matching route in its routing

00:08:22.919 --> 00:08:27.560
table, and forwards it out of the appropriate
interface to the next hop.

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:30.940
Or to the destination, if its directly connected.

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:35.830
It also de-encapsulates the original Layer
2 header, and re-encapsulates with a new header

00:08:35.830 --> 00:08:39.130
destined for the next hop’s MAC address.

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:41.920
All of these functions are part of the data
plane.

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:47.320
Likewise, a switch receives a message, looks
at the destination MAC address, and forwards

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:49.920
it out of the appropriate interface.

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:53.560
Or it floods it out of all interfaces when
appropriate.

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:58.290
This also includes functions like adding or
removing dot1q VLAN tags.

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:03.460
Also, functions like NAT, which changes the
source and/or destination addresses before

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:05.510
forwarding, is part of the data plane.

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:08.770
It’s part of the process of forwarding a
message.

00:09:08.770 --> 00:09:15.140
Also, deciding to forward or discard a message
due to ACLs, port security, etc is part of

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:17.150
the data plane.

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:20.950
Note that another name for the data plane
is the forwarding plane, because that’s

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:21.950
what it does.

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:23.170
It forwards messages.

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:26.060
Here’s an example with two routers.

00:09:26.060 --> 00:09:31.680
R1 receives a packet, and the data plane processes
the packet to forward it out of another interface

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.450
to R2.

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:38.650
And then R2’s data plane processes the packet
to forward it out of another interface.

00:09:38.650 --> 00:09:42.480
In this instance R2 discarded a packet from
R1.

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:46.400
Perhaps an ACL configured on R2’s interface
caused it to make that decision.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:49.600
Anyway, that’s an action of the data plane.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:53.790
Next, let’s look at the control plane.

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:57.530
How does a device’s data plane make its
forwarding decisions?

00:09:57.530 --> 00:10:01.180
How can a router choose which interface to
forward a packet out of?

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:04.230
How does it know what the next hop is?

00:10:04.230 --> 00:10:09.200
Devices use things like their routing table,
MAC address table, ARP table, STP, among other

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:12.540
things, to make these forwarding decisions.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:16.770
Functions that build these tables, and other
functions that influence the data plane, are

00:10:16.770 --> 00:10:18.540
part of the control plane.

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:23.820
So, the control plane controls what the data
plane does, for example by building the router’s

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:25.570
routing table.

00:10:25.570 --> 00:10:29.230
The functions of the control plane are considered
overhead work.

00:10:29.230 --> 00:10:32.330
Let me explain that statement with some examples.

00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:37.760
The OSPF protocol itself doesn’t forward
user data packets, but it informs the data

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.460
plane about how packets should be forwarded.

00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:46.600
Likewise, STP itself isn’t directly involved
in the process of forwarding frames, but it

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:51.270
informs the data plane about which interfaces
should and shouldn’t be used to forward

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:52.720
frames.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:58.060
One more example, ARP messages aren’t user
data, but they are used to build an ARP table

00:10:58.060 --> 00:11:00.400
which is used in the process of forwarding
data.

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:06.140
So, I think you can get an idea of what is
involved in the control plane.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:08.580
Let me demonstrate again with a diagram.

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:13.880
R1 and R2 communicate using OSPF, and this
allows both of them to build their routing

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.680
tables.

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:19.350
These routing tables control the actions of
the data plane, which is where the actual

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.020
forwarding of data packets takes place.

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:26.970
So, in traditional networking the data plane
and control plane are both distributed.

00:11:26.970 --> 00:11:31.670
Each device has its own data plane and its
own control plane, so they are distributed

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:32.860
throughout the network.

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:37.880
It’s not one centralized control plane that
controls the entire network.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:43.600
This is different than in software-defined
networking, which we’ll look at shortly.

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:46.270
Finally let’s look at the management plane.

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:50.100
Like the control plane, the management plane
performs overhead work.

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:54.420
However, the management plane doesn’t directly
affect the forwarding of messages in the data

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:55.490
plane.

00:11:55.490 --> 00:12:00.250
Instead, it consists of protocols that are
used to manage devices.

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:05.320
For example, SSH and Telnet, which are used
to connect to the CLI of a device to configure

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:07.050
and manage it.

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:12.120
Or Syslog, which is used to keep logs of events
that occur on the device.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:17.610
Also SNMP, which is mainly used to monitor
the operations and status of the device.

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:22.960
NTP is another example, which is used to maintain
accurate time on the device.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:28.950
There’s not much else to say about the management
plane, it’s fairly self-explanatory.

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:32.540
And here’s an example of management plane
operations.

00:12:32.540 --> 00:12:38.120
A network engineer uses SSH to connect to
the routers and do some configurations.

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:42.880
For example, perhaps he configured OSPF and
now the control planes of the routers are

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.730
using OSPF to exchange routing information.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:50.290
This then determines how packets are forwarded
in the data plane.

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:54.330
And that’s a basic summary of how these
three logical planes work.

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:58.910
The data plane is really the essential one,
it’s the reason we buy routers and switches.

00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:01.260
We want them to forward messages.

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:05.390
But in order for the data plane to do its
job, we need the control plane and the management

00:13:05.390 --> 00:13:08.500
plane.

00:13:08.500 --> 00:13:12.140
Before wrapping up this section I want to
give a little bit more detail about the data

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:13.910
plane.

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:18.880
The operations of the management plane and
control plane are usually managed by the CPU

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:20.150
of the device.

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:25.670
However, this is not desirable for data plane
operations because CPU processing is slow,

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:26.920
relatively speaking.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:34.380
So, instead a specialized hardware ASIC, application-specific
integrated circuit, is used.

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:40.140
These are chips built for specific purposes,
such as forwarding frames in a switch.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:43.730
Here is a picture from Wikipedia of some ASICs.

00:13:43.730 --> 00:13:47.780
Let me use a switch as an example to demonstrate
how this works.

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:53.910
When a frame is received, the ASIC, not the
CPU, is responsible for the switching logic.

00:13:53.910 --> 00:13:59.260
Remember, this is a specialized chip designed
for forwarding frames, unlike the general-purpose

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:00.320
CPU.

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:06.880
Also, the MAC address table is stored in a
kind of memory called TCAM, ternary content-addressable

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:07.880
memory.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:12.000
TCAM allows for very fast lookups of MAC addresses.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.340
Definitely remember that term, TCAM.

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:20.030
Also note that another common name for the
MAC address table is CAM table, content addressable

00:14:20.030 --> 00:14:21.700
memory table.

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:27.260
So, the ASIC feeds the destination MAC address
of the frame into the TCAM, which returns

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:31.470
the matching MAC address table entry, and
then it is forwarded out of the appropriate

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:33.620
interface.

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:37.930
Note that modern routers also use a similar
hardware data plane, with an ASIC designed

00:14:37.930 --> 00:14:42.170
for forwarding logic and the necessary tables
stored in TCAM.

00:14:42.170 --> 00:14:47.890
So, to summarize this: when a device receives
control or management traffic, destined for

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:52.390
the device itself, it will be processed in
the CPU.

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:56.850
However when a device receives data traffic
which should pass through the device, it is

00:14:56.850 --> 00:15:00.530
processed by the ASIC for maximum speed.

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:06.220
Note that not all data plane traffic is processed
by the ASIC, sometimes the CPU is necessary,

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:08.910
but for now I won’t go any further into
this topic.

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:12.570
We can leave that for CCNP-level studies.

00:15:12.570 --> 00:15:18.310
So, the reason I spent all of that time going
over the logical planes is that they are essential

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:23.050
to understanding the next concept, software-defined
networking.

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:28.100
SDN is an approach to networking that centralizes
the control plane into an application called

00:15:28.100 --> 00:15:29.330
a controller.

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:32.410
Now, this isn’t a new concept for you.

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:37.240
You should be familiar with it already from
learning about wireless LAN controllers.

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:43.070
When using a WLC, many functions are removed
from the APs and centralized in the controller,

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:47.940
so the APs role primarily becomes just forwarding
traffic.

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:54.800
Note that SDN can also be called software-defined
architecture or controller-based networking.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:16:00.110
As I said earlier, traditional control planes
use a distributed architecture, for example

00:16:00.110 --> 00:16:05.480
each router runs OSPF, shares routing information
with other routers, and then independently

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:08.890
calculates its preferred routes to each destination.

00:16:08.890 --> 00:16:15.550
An SDN controller centralizes control plane
functions like calculating routes.

00:16:15.550 --> 00:16:20.180
Note that that is just an example, and how
much of the control plane is centralized varies

00:16:20.180 --> 00:16:21.360
greatly.

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:26.410
There are many different SDN solutions available,
and the role of the controller and the network

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:28.690
devices varies in each solution.

00:16:28.690 --> 00:16:34.180
A controller can interact programmatically
with the network devices using APIs.

00:16:34.180 --> 00:16:37.660
APIs are application programming interfaces.

00:16:37.660 --> 00:16:42.220
I’m sure that many of you have heard of
this term, even though you might not be 100%

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:44.420
sure exactly what it means.

00:16:44.420 --> 00:16:48.990
I will dedicate a video to APIs later, so
I’ll explain them at that point, although

00:16:48.990 --> 00:16:51.480
I will briefly introduce them in this video.

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:55.690
So, here’s our traditional architecture.

00:16:55.690 --> 00:16:59.360
Note that for the purpose of this discussion
I’m leaving the management plane out.

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:02.770
We’re just focusing on the functions of
the control plane.

00:17:02.770 --> 00:17:07.350
Now I’ve removed the control planes from
R1 and R2.

00:17:07.350 --> 00:17:13.040
Then, we have a controller, an application
running on a centralized server, and the control

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:16.100
plane of the network is centralized here.

00:17:16.100 --> 00:17:21.839
Instead of R1 and R2 using OSPF to exchange
routing information and then calculate routes,

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:26.360
the controller communicates with R1 and R2
to program their data planes.

00:17:26.360 --> 00:17:32.260
So, instead of the control plane being distributed,
each router having its own control plane,

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:34.200
it is centralized in the controller.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:39.020
I’m only showing two routers here, but this
could be a network with hundreds of routers,

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:43.880
and this controller would operate the control
plane of the entire network.

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:47.890
The communication between the devices and
the controller is done via what’s called

00:17:47.890 --> 00:17:50.530
the southbound interface, SBI.

00:17:50.530 --> 00:17:56.110
It’s called southbound because in diagrams
we usually draw the controller on top and

00:17:56.110 --> 00:17:59.650
the network devices on the bottom, the south.

00:17:59.650 --> 00:18:03.730
Note that this term doesn’t refer to any
physical interface on a device, but rather

00:18:03.730 --> 00:18:09.520
a software interface that is used to allow
the controller and network devices to communicate.

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:14.600
Now, before moving on to the next slide I
want to repeat that, although this diagram

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:20.590
shows a totally centralized control plane,
in reality there are many different solutions.

00:18:20.590 --> 00:18:25.070
Some of them centralize the entire control
plane, and some of them only centralize some

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:28.750
functions of the control plane.

00:18:28.750 --> 00:18:33.000
So let’s look at SBIs, southbound interfaces.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:38.410
The SBI is used for communications between
the controller and the network devices it

00:18:38.410 --> 00:18:39.410
controls.

00:18:39.410 --> 00:18:46.000
In the diagram, R1 and R2 are controlled by
the controller, and the SBI is used to communicate

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.770
between them.

00:18:47.770 --> 00:18:53.570
The SBI typically consists of a communication
protocol and API, application programming

00:18:53.570 --> 00:18:55.430
interface.

00:18:55.430 --> 00:18:58.900
As I said before we’ll cover APIs in another
video.

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:03.300
But basically, they are used to facilitate
data exchanges between programs.

00:19:03.300 --> 00:19:07.990
The controller is a program, and the network
devices are programs too, running within their

00:19:07.990 --> 00:19:08.990
hardware.

00:19:08.990 --> 00:19:14.840
So, data is exchanged between the controller
and the network devices, and for example an

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:19.630
API on the network device can allow the controller
to access information on them, control their

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:22.740
data plane tables that are used to forward
packets, etc.

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:29.670
APIs play a big role in automating networking
tasks, so we’ll go more in depth later.

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:32.880
Here are some examples of south bound interfaces.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:38.660
OpenFlow, Cisco OpFlex, Cisco onePK, and NETCONF.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:43.240
I will cover some of these in more detail
in later videos, but for now I recommend just

00:19:43.240 --> 00:19:48.650
memorizing their names and remembering that
they are southbound interfaces, used by the

00:19:48.650 --> 00:19:53.520
controller to communicate with the devices
it controls.

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:57.820
In addition to the southbound interface, there
is also a northbound interface.

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:03.880
So, to review, using the SBI the controller
communicates with the managed devices and

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:06.240
gathers information about them.

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:11.660
For example, which devices are in the network,
the topology, so how the devices are connected

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:12.870
together.

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:17.700
Which interfaces are available on the device,
their configurations, such as IP addresses

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:19.770
etc, and much more information.

00:20:19.770 --> 00:20:22.740
That’s what the SBI is used for.

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:28.500
The northbound interface, NBI, is what allows
us to interact with the controller, access

00:20:28.500 --> 00:20:33.550
the data it gathers about the network, program
the controller, and makes changes in the network

00:20:33.550 --> 00:20:35.430
via the SBI.

00:20:35.430 --> 00:20:40.270
We can tell the controller to make a change,
and it will make the change via the SBI.

00:20:40.270 --> 00:20:46.420
So, here we have an app, and it will use the
northbound interface to communicate with the

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:47.420
controller.

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:51.810
I explained the name southbound interface
already, so I think you can guess why this

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:54.150
is called the northbound interface.

00:20:54.150 --> 00:21:01.090
A REST API is used on the controller as an
interface for the apps to interact with it.

00:21:01.090 --> 00:21:04.730
REST stands for representational state transfer,
by the way.

00:21:04.730 --> 00:21:08.559
I’ll explain REST APIs more in the API video.

00:21:08.559 --> 00:21:12.800
Just note that REST isn’t a specific API,
but a type of API.

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:16.210
So, there is an interface on the controller.

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:20.990
As I mentioned earlier, this isn’t a physical
interface, but rather a software interface,

00:21:20.990 --> 00:21:25.980
it’s code that facilitates communication
between the controller and the apps.

00:21:25.980 --> 00:21:32.900
So, the app sends a GET message to the API
for example, which is a request for some data.

00:21:32.900 --> 00:21:39.340
The controller will reply with the requested
data in a structured format like JSON or XML.

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:41.900
Perhaps you’ve heard of JSON or XML before.

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:46.140
I’ll make a separate video explaining them,
but for now just understand that they are

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:48.680
standard formats for structuring data.

00:21:48.680 --> 00:21:50.980
Why should data be structured?

00:21:50.980 --> 00:21:55.500
It makes it much easier for programs to use
the data, because its stored in a standard

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:57.800
format that is easy to interact with.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:03.510
Okay, that was a basic overview of the main
components of SDN architecture.

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:07.650
Before wrapping up the video, let’s spend
some more time comparing it with traditional

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:08.650
networks.

00:22:08.650 --> 00:22:14.530
So, we’ve been looking at SDN a lot, but
networking tasks can be automated in traditional

00:22:14.530 --> 00:22:16.500
network architectures too.

00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:21.580
For example, scripts can be written, for example
in Python, to push commands to many devices

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:23.050
at once.

00:22:23.050 --> 00:22:27.670
The script can enable your computer to SSH
to the device and then push whatever commands

00:22:27.670 --> 00:22:31.550
you want, perhaps configuring VLANs on many
switches.

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:36.700
Also, Python with good use of regular expressions
can parse through show commands to gather

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:39.670
information about the network devices.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:43.790
If you don’t know what regular expressions
are you can google it, but basically they

00:22:43.790 --> 00:22:48.090
are just ways of searching for patterns in
text.

00:22:48.090 --> 00:22:52.010
Look at this SHOW command for example, SHOW
INTERFACES.

00:22:52.010 --> 00:22:56.510
This is in a human-readable format, it’s
pretty simple for us to read through this

00:22:56.510 --> 00:22:59.260
and get what information we need.

00:22:59.260 --> 00:23:04.150
For example, if you want to know the bandwidth
you can just look here and see BW 1,000,000

00:23:04.150 --> 00:23:06.900
kilobits per second, so 1 gig.

00:23:06.900 --> 00:23:12.700
You can write a script that does the same,
it could SSH to the device, use the SHOW INTERFACES

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:17.260
command, and then parse through the output
with regular expressions to find the information

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:18.790
you want.

00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:25.650
However, the robust and centralized data collected
by SDN controllers greatly facilitates these

00:23:25.650 --> 00:23:27.050
functions.

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:31.140
The controller collects robust information
about all devices in the network, providing

00:23:31.140 --> 00:23:33.720
a network-wide view.

00:23:33.720 --> 00:23:38.850
Also the northbound APIs allow apps to access
information in a format that is easy for programs

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:43.580
to understand, formats such as JSON or XML.

00:23:43.580 --> 00:23:47.750
No need to write scripts to parse through
specific SHOW commands to get the information

00:23:47.750 --> 00:23:49.080
you want.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:54.590
Also, having this centralized data facilitates
network-wide analytics, rather than getting

00:23:54.590 --> 00:24:00.680
information from individual devices and having
to correlate the data yourself.

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:05.620
SDN tools provide the benefits of automation
without the requirement of third-party apps

00:24:05.620 --> 00:24:07.380
and scripts.

00:24:07.380 --> 00:24:12.940
This also means that you don’t need expertise
in automation to make use of SDN tools.

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:17.990
Many of them are very easy to use even for
those who are unable to write their own scripts.

00:24:17.990 --> 00:24:23.120
However, APIs allow third-party applications
to interact with the controller, which can

00:24:23.120 --> 00:24:26.490
be very powerful if you’re able to create
your own apps.

00:24:26.490 --> 00:24:32.950
To summarize, although SDN and automation
aren’t the same thing, SDN is just one aspect

00:24:32.950 --> 00:24:38.300
of network automation, the SDN architecture
greatly facilitates the automation of various

00:24:38.300 --> 00:24:44.120
tasks in the network via the SDN controller
and APIs.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:50.300
In this video we covered various topics related
to network automation, and SDN in particular.

00:24:50.300 --> 00:24:52.850
We didn’t really go in depth, but that’s
fine.

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:57.809
This is an introductory video to the automation
section of the course which will be 4 or 5

00:24:57.809 --> 00:25:01.890
videos in total, so we have plenty of time
to learn the details.

00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:06.540
But network automation is a paradigm shift
compared to traditional networking, so instead

00:25:06.540 --> 00:25:11.251
of digging into the details right away I think
it’s best to get a general overview of the

00:25:11.251 --> 00:25:13.150
important topics.

00:25:13.150 --> 00:25:19.970
In the next video we’ll look at data serialization,
such as JSON and XML, in more detail.

00:25:19.970 --> 00:25:23.840
This is an important topic because it puts
data in a format that is easy for programs

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:25.970
to understand and work with.

00:25:25.970 --> 00:25:30.380
Okay, let’s go into the quiz for today,
and make sure to watch until the end of the

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:36.360
quiz for a bonus question from Boson Software’s
ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for

00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:37.360
the CCNA.

00:25:37.360 --> 00:25:43.110
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:25:43.110 --> 00:25:45.750
Which of the following are benefits of network
automation?

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:47.140
(select two).

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:52.380
Pause the video now to select the best answers,
select two.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:26:00.600
Okay, the answers are A, reduced human error,
and B, reduced OpEx.

00:26:00.600 --> 00:26:03.940
Because automation means network engineers
don’t have to spend so much time inputting

00:26:03.940 --> 00:26:08.820
commands into the CLI, human error such as
typos can be reduced.

00:26:08.820 --> 00:26:14.970
Also, tasks can be achieved in a much shorter
period of time, which reduces the OpEx, operating

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:16.260
expenses, of the network.

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:20.470
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:26:20.470 --> 00:26:22.090
Which of the following are SBIs?

00:26:22.090 --> 00:26:23.540
(select two).

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:27.910
Pause the video now to select the best answers.

00:26:27.910 --> 00:26:34.490
Okay, the answers are C, OpenFlow and D, OpFlex.

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:39.410
Other examples of SBIs given in this video
are Cisco onePK and NETCONF.

00:26:39.410 --> 00:26:45.170
We’ll cover some of them in detail later,
but for now just remember that they are SBIs,

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:46.190
southbound interfaces.

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:49.980
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:26:49.980 --> 00:26:56.200
Which of the following network functions would
you expect to be centralized in SDN?

00:26:56.200 --> 00:27:00.170
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:00.170 --> 00:27:06.170
Okay, the answer is A, calculating routes.

00:27:06.170 --> 00:27:11.820
B, C, and D are all data plane functions,
they describe functions involved in forwarding

00:27:11.820 --> 00:27:12.820
messages.

00:27:12.820 --> 00:27:17.460
A, calculating routes, is a function of the
control plane and will likely be centralized

00:27:17.460 --> 00:27:18.860
in an SDN architecture.

00:27:18.860 --> 00:27:24.510
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:27:24.510 --> 00:27:28.120
What is the purpose of the SBI in SDN architecture?

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:32.640
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:39.840
Okay, the answer is C, to facilitate data
exchange between the controller and network

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:41.270
devices.

00:27:41.270 --> 00:27:46.179
For review, here’s that diagram again showing
the role of the southbound interface.

00:27:46.179 --> 00:27:52.010
Regarding option B, it is the northbound interface,
NBI, that facilitates data exchange between

00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:54.780
the controller and apps, not the SBI.

00:27:54.780 --> 00:28:00.220
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:04.280
Which of the logical planes of networking
does NTP’s function fit in?

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:08.809
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:28:08.809 --> 00:28:13.700
Okay, the answer is B, management plane.

00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:17.830
NTP is used to provide accurate time for the
device.

00:28:17.830 --> 00:28:22.110
It is not involved in the forwarding of messages,
and it does not control how the data plane

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:23.110
operates.

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:25.880
Instead, it operates at the management plane.

00:28:25.880 --> 00:28:28.690
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:28:28.690 --> 00:28:34.128
Now let’s look at a bonus question in Boson
Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

